Saw a family of 3 discussing over the items at our Kek Ai Tiam aka provision shop at O'My Kampong Cafe. It's really heart warming to know that the uncle on the far right sharing with his children (we think) on why this is called Kek Ai Tiam in the olden days. "Kek Ai" is actually a Hokkien word used by the Chinese living in the Kampong Village, referring it as a provision shop. It is actually derived from the Malay word "Kedai" which means "shop". So when the Chinese heard from their Malay neighbours calling it Kedai, the Chinese community had come out with their own version of calling it "Kekai". Do you have any Kampong stories that you can share with us? Share with us on the comments section so the youngsters can also learn what is actually a Kampong Village in the olden days :).
